<div class="container warning" id="problem_statement">
    <div class="container-header">Problem Statement</div>
    <div class="container-content">
        <div class="container-content-inner">
            <h3>Issue Description</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Symptom</strong>: Docker container accepts connections on port 3000 but returns empty response/timeout</li>
                <li><strong>Container Status</strong>: Running but marked as "unhealthy"</li>
                <li><strong>Application Status</strong>: Runs normally from command line (perl script/comserv_server.pl)</li>
                <li><strong>Environment</strong>: docker-compose up (development setup)</li>
                <li><strong>Port Mapping</strong>: 3000:3000 (host:container)</li>
            </ul>
            
            <h3>Expected Behavior</h3>
            <p>When accessing http://localhost:3000, the Comserv Perl/Catalyst application should serve the web interface with full HTML content and functionality.</p>
            
            <h3>Actual Behavior</h3>
            <p>Connection attempt results in timeout or connection refused error. No application content is served.</p>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>

<div class="container info" id="root_cause">
    <div class="container-header">Root Cause Analysis - PERMISSION DENIED ERROR</div>
    <div class="container-content">
        <div class="container-content-inner">
            <h3>Primary Issue: EACCES (Permission Denied)</h3>
            
            <p><strong>Error Found in Container Logs:</strong></p>
            <pre><code>2025-12-17 04:25:08,076 INFO spawnerr: unknown error making dispatchers for 'comserv-server': EACCES
2025-12-17 04:25:09,078 INFO spawnerr: unknown error making dispatchers for 'comserv-server': EACCES
2025-12-17 04:25:11,083 INFO spawnerr: unknown error making dispatchers for 'comserv-server': EACCES
2025-12-17 04:25:14,125 INFO gave up: comserv-server entered FATAL state, too many start retries too quickly</code></pre>
            
            <h3>What's Happening</h3>
            <ol>
                <li><strong>Supervisord starts successfully</strong> - The supervisor process manager launches as PID 1 (running as root)</li>
                <li><strong>Supervisor tries to launch comserv-server</strong> - It attempts to fork a new process for the Perl application</li>
                <li><strong>Permission denied on log files</strong> - The comserv user cannot write to /opt/comserv/root/log/catalyst.log and catalyst_error.log</li>
                <li><strong>Process fails to start</strong> - Without writable log destinations, supervisor abandons the process</li>
                <li><strong>Port 3000 remains unbound</strong> - No application listens on port 3000, connection times out</li>
            </ol>
            
            <h3>Root Cause: Insufficient Directory Permissions</h3>
            
            <p>In <code>docker-entrypoint.sh</code> (lines 91-93):</p>
            <pre><code>mkdir -p ${CATALYST_HOME}/root/log /var/log/supervisor
chmod 755 ${CATALYST_HOME}/root/log /var/log/supervisor</code></pre>
            
            <p><strong>Problem</strong>: The log directory is created with <code>chmod 755</code>, which means:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Owner (root)</strong>: read, write, execute (7)</li>
                <li><strong>Group</strong>: read, execute only (5) - <strong>NO WRITE</strong></li>
                <li><strong>Others</strong>: read, execute only (5) - <strong>NO WRITE</strong></li>
            </ul>
            
            <p>When supervisor tries to write log files as the <code>comserv</code> user, the user lacks write permissions on the directory.</p>
            
            <h3>Why This Happens</h3>
            <p>Even though the Dockerfile correctly does <code>chown -R comserv:comserv /opt/comserv</code> during build, the entrypoint script runs AFTER container startup and recreates the directories with root ownership and restrictive permissions (755).</p>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>

